附加记录：    

If that's the case, I'd like to direct your attention to this:



As the device was designed as a proof-of-concept prototype, no particular attention was paid to how an SCP would actually be placed into the core; it was assumed this could be engineered into a later version of the device.
附加记录：    

So, they didn't think getting an actual SCP into the thing would be important in the first design phase? What if later alterations made it so the thing wouldn't work if they put in a way to place an SCP within it? What if the weight of an SCP in there made the whole thing go off-kilter and irradiate the entire area? These are things you would realistically take into account, even in the first design phase.

Also, I would like to point out: in most cases, Special Containment Procedures are tailor-made to the SCP in question. For example, placing 105 in a giant chamber at the bottom of the sea would make no sense. What is this intended to contain in the first place? Sure, it could contain something like 076 (somehow), but what about 682? 106? 239?





